🌌 LEVEL 2: Navigation (Star Mapping)
You cannot fly blind through an asteroid field, Commander. The stock market is not random — it is driven by the collective psychology of millions of buyers and sellers. That psychology leaves repeating patterns on price charts. Technical Analysis is the discipline of reading those patterns.

2.1 Star Charts (Candlestick Anatomy)
Every candlestick tells the story of a battle between Buyers (Bulls) and Sellers (Bears) during one time period.

* OPEN: The price when the period started.
* HIGH: The highest point reached — where sellers overwhelmed buyers.
* LOW: The lowest point reached — where buyers stepped back in.
* CLOSE: The final price. The verdict of the battle.

🟢 Green Candle: Buyers won. Price closed ABOVE the open. Bullish.
🔴 Red Candle: Sellers won. Price closed BELOW the open. Bearish.

* Upper Wick: Price tried to go higher — sellers rejected it.
* Lower Wick: Price tried to go lower — buyers rescued it.

Key Candlestick Patterns:
* Hammer: Long lower wick, small body at top. Buyers violently rejected a sell-off. Strong bullish reversal at downtrend bottoms.
* Shooting Star: Long upper wick, small body at bottom. Sellers rejected a rally at the top. Bearish reversal.
* Doji: Open and Close nearly identical. No winner. Market is in pure indecision — watch the next candle.
* Bullish Engulfing: A massive green candle swallows the entire previous red candle. Institutional buying surge.
* Bearish Engulfing: A massive red candle swallows the previous green candle. Institutional selling surge.

Timeframe Rule: Always analyze Top-Down. Start Weekly → Daily → Hourly. Only trade in the direction the Daily chart supports.

2.2 Gravitational Pull (Trend Analysis)
The Dow Theory (1900): The market moves in trends. Established trends tend to persist until proven otherwise.

* Uptrend: Higher Highs (HH) + Higher Lows (HL). Each peak and trough is higher than the last. Strategy: Buy on pullbacks to higher lows.
* Downtrend: Lower Highs (LH) + Lower Lows (LL). Strategy: Avoid buying. Wait for reversal confirmation.
* Sideways/Consolidation: Price oscillates in a flat range. Market is gathering energy. Strategy: Do nothing. Wait for the breakout.

Golden Rule: Never fight the trend. Trade with the wind at your back.

2.3 Shield and Ceiling Placements (Support and Resistance)
* Support (The Shield): A price floor where buyers repeatedly step in. The more times it holds, the stronger it becomes.
* Resistance (The Ceiling): A price ceiling where sellers repeatedly push price back down.

Role Reversal (The Most Important Concept):
* When resistance is decisively broken, it becomes the new support.
* When support is decisively broken, it becomes the new resistance.
* This is why professionals re-enter positions at old breakout levels on pullbacks.

Breakout vs Fakeout:
✅ Real Breakout: Price closes convincingly above resistance on HIGH volume.
❌ Fakeout: Brief cross of the line on thin volume, immediately fails. Engineered by institutions to stop-hunt retail traders.

2.4 Navigation Tools (Indicators)
Moving Averages (SMA / EMA): Smooth price data to reveal the underlying trend.
* 50-Day MA: Medium-term institutional reference.
* 200-Day MA: The most-watched line in the world. Long-term trend indicator.
🟡 Golden Cross: 50-day crosses ABOVE 200-day. Major bull signal.
🔴 Death Cross: 50-day crosses BELOW 200-day. Major bear signal.

RSI (Relative Strength Index): Momentum oscillator. Range: 0-100.
* Above 70 = Overbought. Correction likely. Do NOT chase.
* Below 30 = Oversold. Bounce likely. Potential buy zone.
* Bearish Divergence (Advanced): Price makes a new high, but RSI does not. Hidden weakness. Reversal incoming.

Volume: The single greatest confirmation tool.
* High volume breakout = Real institutional move. Act on it.
* Low volume breakout = Retail speculation. Almost always a fakeout.

